Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: To Seal Victim/Witness Identification Key, signed by Judge Michael O. Bohren on October 20, 2022.

Defendant to comply with I.D. Processing. Absolute sobriety, defendant is not to possess or consume any alcohol. Defendant is not to use/possess any controlled substances without a valid prescription and take as prescribed. Defendant not to possess any drug paraphernalia. Defendant is not to possess any dangerous weapons/firearms/knives. Defendant to have no VIOLENT contact with Victim A/Victim B/Victim C listed in the Criminal Complaint/Victim Identification Key.  Defendant is not to share, reproduce or distribute any personal and/or identifying information about the crime victim(s), except to their attorney. Defendant is to comply with an Civil Court orders.

3:32 PM Defendant Jack H Large in court, in custody.  Attorney Justin G Griffis in court for Jack H Large.  Prosecuting attorney Patrick Ryan Campbell in court for the State of Wisconsin. Attorney Griffis appears as friend of the court. Defendant was not evaluated by the public defender's office, as the list indicated he was released. Defense acknowledges receipt of complaint and waives reading of complaint. Service admitted/advised of charges and potential penalties. Court advises of right to an attorney. Defendant to apply at Public Defender's Office for representation. NOT GUILTY PLEA ENTERED BY COURT.
